"1256","1254":"1254","about 1278":"circa 1278","about 1276":"circa 1276","Great Fulford, Devon, England":"Great Fulford, Devon, England"},"en":{"1252–before 1303":"1252–before 1303","1252–1303":"1252–1303","1252–Male":"1252–Deceased","1254–Male":"1254–Deceased","1256–Male":"1256–Deceased","1252–1302":"1252–1302","1278–1347":"1278–1347","1280–1349":"1280–1349","1220–1295":"1220–1295","1225–Female":"1225–Deceased","before 1303":"before 1303","about 1280":"about 1280","1220":"1220","1252":"1252","1295":"1295","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","1303":"1303","1302":"1302","1225":"1225","1278":"1278","1256":"1256","1254":"1254","about 1278":"about 1278","about 1276":"about 1276","Great Fulford, Devon, England":"Great Fulford, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Fulford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named in Devon, such as Fulford in Tiverton, Great Fulford in Dunsford, Fullaford in High Bray, Fulford Bridge in Shebbear, Fullaford in Sampford Courtenay, and Fullaford in Buckfastleigh.","habitational name from one or more of the various places so called elsewhere in England, such as Fulford (Staffordshire), Fulford in Kingston Saint Mary (Somerset), Gate Fulford and Water Fulford (both East Yorkshire), Fulfords Farm in Itchingfield (Sussex), and Fulforth in Witton Gilbert (Durham). All places in 1 above and 2 are named from Old English <i>fūl</i> ‘dirty, muddy’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":7,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":38,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Fulford was born in 1252, in Great Fulford, Devon, England, his father, William de Fulford, was 33 and his mother, Mariot de Belston, was 27. He married Mrs Henry De Fulford about 1276, in Great Fulford, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died before 1303, in his hometown."},"et":{"1252–before 1303":"1252–enne 1303","1252–1303":"1252–1303","1252–Male":"1252–Surnud","1254–Male":"1254–Surnud","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","12